<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870424-0125 </DOCNO><HL> Medicine andamp; Health (A Special Report): Fighting Back---Where to LearnAbout Advances</HL><DD> 04/24/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTPHARMACEUTICALS, HOSPITAL SUPPLIES, MANAGEMENT (PHA) </IN><TEXT>   News of cancer-treatment advances and listings of services are offered through several government and private programs.    The National Cancer Institute: For doctors only, an institute-sponsored computerized data base holds names of 12,000 cancer specialists, provides updates on new treatments and lists researchers who are testing new therapies as well as requirements for including a patient in those tests.    For the public, the institute has a Cancer Information Service available through a toll-free number to answer questions about new and experimental treatments, general cancer information, community support services and local cancer specialists. The number is 1-800-4-CANCER.    The American Cancer Society: Its Cancer Response System, which offers up-to-date information on medical science to the public, can be reached by calling, toll-free, 1-800-ACS-2345. Local branches of the society also provide a variety of information and support programs. </TEXT></DOC>